1215","1235":"1235","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1253":"1253","1272":"1272","about 1253":"about 1253","1270":"1270","Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Grendon, Warwickshire, England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England","Grendon,Warwickshire,England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Grendon, North Warwickshire, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grendon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Grendon (in Witheridge and in Tavistock, Devon), Grendon (Northants, Warwicks), Grendon Underwood (Bucks), Grendon Bishop, Grendon Warren (Herefs), or Grindon (Durham, Northumb, Staffs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Grundon","meanings":["English: variant of  <i>Grindon</i>,  see  Grendon  ."]},{"name":"Grindon","meanings":["English:  see  Grendon  ."]}]},{"name":"Justice","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name from Middle English <i>justice</i>, <i>justis(e)</i> ‘judicial officer; judge’, Old French <i>justise</i>, <i>justice</i> ‘uprightness; equity; vindication of right; court of justice; judge’, Latin <i>iustitia</i>, a derivative of <i>iustus</i> (see   Just  ).","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, because of its literal meaning in English ‘uprightness; equity; vindication of right’."],"variants":[{"name":"Justiss","meanings":["English: variant of   Justice  ."]},{"name":"Justis","meanings":["English: variant of   Justice  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jestice","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Justice  ."]},{"name":"Just","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Christoph, Ernst, Gerhart, Heinz, Helmut, Hildegarde, Horst, Otto, Reinhard, Reinhold.","English, Scottish, German, Danish, Catalan, French, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, Croatian, and Hungarian: from a personal name, from Latin <i>Justus</i>, from <i>justus</i> ‘just, upright’. There were several early Christian saints of this name, among them a 4th-century bishop of Lyon and a 6th-century bishop of Urgell in Catalonia. Compare   Yust  .","English: occasionally perhaps from a nickname, whether French or English, meaning ‘the just one’."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese (<b>Ōi</b>): written 大井 ‘large well’. It is found in central and eastern Japan.","Japanese (<b>Ōi</b>): written 多 ‘many’. It was pronounced <b>Oho</b> in ancient times and is listed in the <i>Shinsen shōjiroku</i>. It is not common in modern Japan.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 黃, see   Huang   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Huang","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Wei, Ming, Jian, Ying, Yi, Jing, Wen, Jin, Ping, Min, Yong, Cheng, Hong, Chong, Chang, Pao, Sha, Shen, Tun, You, Chung, Shiu, Ti, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 黄, meaning ‘yellow’ in Chinese: (i) from Huang (黃), the name of an ancient state (present-day Huangchuan in Henan province)annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) traced back to some minority ethnic groups in ancient southern China."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Firm and resolute’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert II Grendon - Justice of Assize, Knight was born in 1200, in Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert De Grendon, was -9 and his mother, Avice De Brae, was -14. He died in 1272, in his hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1200–1272":"1200–1272","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1235–1279":"1235–1279","1253–Male":"1253–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1253":"1253","1272":"1272","about 1253":"umbes 1253","1270":"1270","Grendon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grendon, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grendon, Warwickshire, England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, England","Grendon,Warwickshire,England":"Grendon, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grendon, North Warwickshire, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grendon, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1200–1272":"1200–1272","1215–Female":"1215–Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1235–1279":"1235–1279","1253–Male":"1253–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1279"